–1492","about 1492":"about 1492","about 1490":"about 1490","1471":"1471","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1437":"1437","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","about 1455":"about 1455","about 1475":"about 1475","about 1465":"about 1465","about 1471":"about 1471","Coalsnaughton, Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","Harviestoun, Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drysdale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dryfesdale near Dumfries (which is normally pronounced <i>Drysdale</i>), named from the river <i>Dryfe</i> + Old English <i>dæl</i> ‘valley’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Drysdale had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Andrew Drysdale. She died about 1492, in Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland."},"et":{"–about 1492":"–umbes 1492","1437–1490":"1437–1490","1455–Female":"1455–Surnud","1465–Male":"1465–Surnud","1471–Male":"1471–Surnud","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","–1492":"–1492","about 1492":"umbes 1492","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1471":"1471","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1437":"1437","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","about 1455":"umbes 1455","about 1475":"umbes 1475","about 1465":"umbes 1465","about 1471":"umbes 1471","Coalsnaughton, Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","Harviestoun, Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland":"Tillicoultry, Clackmannanshire, Scotland","Tillicoul